be - do so now, but - but - but not at that time, no. Well education is so different now, I mean it's - education has altered so much you see it's quite possible. That time, no. No, no, no, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did your parents take an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Oh yes, they were - oh yes, they did. Do our homework properly and - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did they ask what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Yes, you - yes, they liked to know what we did and - we used to show them the books you see with the - text - text books we had and that sort of thing, they were interested, oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 When you were at work then you kept on with the friends from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Oh yes, yes, yes, they were there yes, unless they'd moved away, but as far as I can remember we did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 D
o you think there was any way in particular in which your life changed in those first three or four years of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
No, I don't think so, as early as twenty, 'cos - no, but you see when I was twenty-one - about - just - just before the arm - the Armis
tice in the first world war, and after that I noticed a change - in between the wars, but I don't think I can remember much about it changing - not during that period. Because life change - began to change after the first world war you see and that's that
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did you ever go to the theatre with another friend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Oh yes, often, when I think of that, we loved the theatre.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 You'd go with friends would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
With friends, yes, or the family or - or even by myself when I got older because - I neve
r mind going by myself, I'd much rather go alone - no, I'd much rather go alone that go with somebody who's going to irritate you by talking or whispering or laughing and everything and I - and I'd far rather go by myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Had you wanted to go to the 
theatre in the West End when you were in your late teens, would that have been all right to go on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
I think so. I - she might not have liked it too much as young as that alone, I don't know, not in the day time she wouldn't have minded but I'm not so sure whether she would have liked it at night in the West End. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
One gets the impression sometimes that young girls were quite sort of heavily chaperoned and restricted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Oh no, we weren't chaperoned in that sense, oh no, but I think
 she would have been a bit nervous if we had been out like that you know. If we went to a dance or anything like that with a young man and brought us home well that's a different thing again - altogether, but not to be entirely alone in the West End I don
't think, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Were you sometimes invited out by a young man on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Oh yes, often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 That would be all right?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Oh yes. As long as mother knew who they were, I mean, she - well she would like to meet them, have some idea of their bac
kground, oh well, that's only natural. Well you might - might - quite right, of course it's quite right. But she - but she was very - broad minded on the whole and - because you see we used to have a lot of my brothers - two brothers friends and we all so
rt of went out in hordes or one - one of you out together you know, we made parties up and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 You first of all went to the religious department?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Yes. And - I did all - all - you see, I was a shorthand typist in the pool where practically everybod
y started you see, that's - it was awfully good practice you see because all the departments were slightly different. And then - no, I don't think I did talks did I, no, I didn't do talks, I did music booking. I don't know whether you - probably may or ma
y
 not have heard of him - he was - Pedro Tillet who was Ibsen Tillet, the - he belonged - it was his - he had this - music agency, anyway, he was a - awfully sweet person and he was sort of head of the - music booking and I loved working in that department
 
terribly, it was really lovely. And then I went down to do the simal - same sort of thing in productions which - which was, as I say covered everything, in the entertainment line, variety - musical comedy, operetta, anything like that. Well then eventuall
y
, the drama side of it always interested me much more than the other, because I'm not a variety lover at all. The drama person asked for me, if I could go back there, a man who was doing it because it was too much for him to cope with by himself. So - I w
a
s very kindly released by this other nice man for whom I worked because he said I know you like drama much better than you do - the other side of it, and there I stayed and - did all this lovely booking for so many years, which was really wonderful. But o
f
 course lots of people might have thought - oh you're very unambitious, you don't want to move, but I felt that I really had a job that I could do, and that I really did adore. And I thought, well what is the good of changing just because of that, I'm muc
h
 happier and I might not have been anything like as successful. After all, twenty-eight years is quite a long time to do one particular job, there are very few people do it all - the same job all that time, and I got, no, I got into the habit of this and 
everybody knew me and - oh practically all the artists are great friends of mine, I mean I used to go and see them outside office and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 all}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311  that sort of thing you see, we - I - really much more like a large family to me. It was lovely, it really was lovely. A
nd of course in the beginning in Savoy Hill you might - might sort of - give you a little idea of what it was like, the people - because I don't suppose there are many left now who are in Savoy Hill anyway. What was the great joy there was that everything
 
was so informal. Well nowadays of course we always call it the funfair crew, because it's so huge. Well naturally of course it's inevitable that that sort of thing would grow, but then it really was fun. For instance, I was - listening one day - I - - I o
n
ly had a little crystal set in those days, and so if there was anything I wanted to hear particularly I used to go to - in the listening room, and - I shall never forget one day - I was listening to a production of journeys end, and suddenly, just outside
 the listening room was the lift, and I just have gone out or something or perhaps it was all over, and there it was on a November the eleventh, it was on Armistice Day, and I can remember - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 Duke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311  of Windsor, he was coming in to make - a - an appeal I su
ppose for poppy day or something, and I mean we - I was standing as near him as you are, well now this is just an instance that - if you - nowadays, when people of - of that - distinguish - so distinguished as that - we would never have been allowed to go
 
anywhere near them. We should have been - I can remember when - one or two people - I know when Queen Mary came once, Queen Mary and King George came to the Concert Hall, and we were all sort of in round, were all sort of shepherded you know and we weren'
t
 allowed - we could see her but I mean there was no informality and that was what was so lovely about it here, you never knew who might meet. It was really lovely in Savoy Hill. And those funny little studios. Oh there were some little studios, which woul
d - which curtains were draped over and all this sort of thing, it really was - it really was lovely, it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 very sad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311  we had to move - it was - most - you know, what I would call a building that was almost falling to pieces, but - it had - oh enormous adven
tures, enormous adventure, and it had a tremendous amount of atmosphere, which BH hasn't got you see, you can't help it in any enormous great place, the atmosphere goes at once. You know what I mean don't you, in any big building, yes, I mean it just goes
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 But you were in bookings when you went to the BBC 'til the end were you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
No, not - well, no, not - I wasn't quite, no, no, not quite, I had two years - round - sort of going from different departments, but then I went to bookings in - May 1928 and there I stayed, until I left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 You say you liked the music department especially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Music - well no, no - I loved - drama - I loved music bookings but I was - really my - I am very fond of music but drama is really my love, and - I was very pl
eased and also I was extremely lucky to get that job, because I mean I might not have done. I mean it just happened that the man who I worked with in productions, who - was an absolute darling, and - he was so nice - and we got on awfully well together, a
nd - I think that's how it really - how it really went on, and that's how I went - eventually to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 drama alone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 . Because - originally the drama wasn't sufficient to be a different - separate department, and then after - oh after a year or so I suppose, it got 
- very much bigger, and the - and the man who did it - who was head of it, he - he needed an assistant and he asked me to come back because he knew that I - knew the work, and that I was interested in drama and - from then on I remained there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did you ever see Lord Reef in the early days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Well - I - the only time I really - had any personal contact with him - because you see, really unless - you had an administrative job, which I didn't have - you hardly really came in contact with him, it was ad
ministrative people did, but - after ten years service, everybody - I suppose it's the same now, it certainly was in my day - he saw you - you got - a I think I got - it was twenty-five - guin - twenty-five pound bonus for ten years service, and - everybo
d
y went to see him. And he was very nice, it was a bit awe inspiring you know, he was a - tremendous height and - and I think that's - I can truthfully say that's the only time I - really came in contact with him personally, I mean I used to see him knock 
a
bout the building, but - the entertainment side of the work didn't really come - approach him at all, you know, it was just not one of those - I think it was mostly the administration and perhaps the personnel, but certainly the administration, was the on
e that came to - that came -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Why was he so awe-inspiring?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Well - I don't know whether you - did you see the pictures of him when he died recently? Well - he was, you see, he was enormously tall, he was about six feet four. And he was a very stra
nge man. He was - deeply religious, not that I mean anything by that at all, but he had tremendous principles and tremendous ideals, and - I - and I can say this in all - in - so far as I'm concerned, and I've heard quite a lot of staff say it too, that w
e
 never had a BG like him, and we haven't. He made the BBC let's face it, rightly or wrongly, and of course he was - Herman - what's the word I want - a little bit biased, and - rather narrow minded in many ways. But - we have never had one that I consider
 
would approach Lord Reef. I mean, then - there's just one of those things I felt and I know a lot of people who were there with me, another friend of mine who - we were both in Savoy Hill together and - she did know him a great deal more than I did becaus
e
 she worked for a high office - an administrative officer, well then her work did come in touch with him you see. But he had a tremendous sense of humour. And I believe people who knew him - like him very well indeed, but I - as I say my only real contact
 with him was that very brief - int - interview I had with him when he - after ten years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Can you explain how you make a booking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Oh, well now, wait - now wait a minute. Yes, I think so. There were four of us doing this work and - we had - now I 
can't remember exactly the number of producers now, but we were all - we - we four - were divided up, or rather shall I say the producers - were divided up between us, and I suppose we had about - oh - between for and six to go-with each. Well how they di
d
 it was - the drama - department who - you've heard of Val Guilguid haven't you, John's brother, well he was - I knew him very well of course because he was in Savoy Hill and he was head of drama department for a long while. And - he - they had a monthly 
m
eeting. And for each month, the plays they were going to do were set out, and divided between the various producers. And it according - and - you - they all - we all had eventually a cast sheet - from these producers, and - they used to put down their det
a
ils of rehearsals, transmission and that sort of thing, and then they'd put down their casts you see, and - they used to - well - whenever possible they gave you about four or five - alternatives you see so that if you couldn't get the first one you got t
h
e second one. And so - a lot of them were - these people were done through agents, you know, the theatrical agents, but on the other hand there were awful lot that - that you got in touch with direct. Well - my - well threequarters of my life was on the t
e
lephone ringing them up, you know, and getting them to ring me back, and - then you - you put an OK against them if they could do it and if they couldn't do certain rehearsal you'd pass that information on to the producer, and if he - didn't want that, if
 
he said I must have everybody - at every rehearsal I have then you go on to his second choice and that sort of thing, until you got the cast complete. Well then I - we - we - four girls had a secretary who did the contracts for us, and we put down the var
i
ous details and that sort of thing and - sent them off and - with their various - fees and that sort of thing, and then they came back signed, and - actually we didn't have anything to do with that but they put naturally the date they went out, they were 
p
ut in a diary, kept in a big diary and that sort of thing. But I think that was the main thing really, and then - in holiday time, when the drama booking manager was away used to go to these meetings which were rather fun really, I used to enjoy that, lis
t
ening to what Val had got to say, and - we had some awfully nice producers. And then we had also - we did a certain amount of booking for the - for the features people. Who did the - you know, who did the feature programmes which are rather like the - sor
t of documentaries they do on Tuesdays. And - they were divided up in the same sort of way, and they were more or less joined together with drama and features went together. But I think - that was the main - main way we did it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 You said you got to know some of the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Oh I did, I got to know - well that was - really quite a natural thing, because you see some of these - so many of them came in - to - to sign their contract - contracts or to see me, or - see any - whoever did their booking you
 see. And if they couldn't do anything or anything like that I used to - oh yes, I - only I wasn't ever known as Lady Stead there because - for - for many many years, I married during the war - and everybody knew me by my maiden name and so I stuck to it,
 I thought well it - it's no good, nobody want - nobody will now who I - oh some of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 artists}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311  know my married name of course, but that's more or less in a personal capacity. But from the point of view of work it was much easier to stick, to the name, my m
aiden name, everybody knew my name, there wasn't any point in changing. But - that's how I really got to know them so well, because by ringing them up and then they'd come in and they'd - also I knew so many of them - but it's rather sad now, I was thinki
n
g the other day - so many of the - men, and women for that matter, whom I knew so well - are getting too old for broadcasting you see, they're more or less my own contemporaries, and - well not of course the young people must have their own - must have th
e
ir say but - young men like yourself for instance, there are so many new ones on television and - and radio, whose names I've never even heard of. Well that's not - that - that's quite understandable because I mean - but it's rather sad sometimes when I t
hink of - how many really wonderful artists we had round about my own age, because they were all more or less my own age in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Who is your favourite artist that you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 What do you mean, as a performer? Or a as person? Oh - oh beca
use - oh now that's very difficult. Oh I have so many I was very fond of so many of them. And - what is awfully sad really is so many of the ones I was fondest of have died. Like for instance - well I don't know whether they would convey anything to you, 
t
heir names, they might, James McKechnie, did you know his name, well I knew Jimmy very well. Then there was - Ivan Sampson whom I was also very fond of, Leslie Perrins. All people who did an enormous amount of work for us in those days. Ernest Jay, well y
o
u might not have known him possibly. These are more radio names than any - than theatre names you know, and then there's - well Norman Cherry is there of course still and - Carlton Hobbs who's always known as Hobbo. Well they were great great friends of m
ine, all that lot. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Val Geilguid was in charge of the department was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Val Geilguid was in charge of the drama department, not the booking. The - the - because the booking - department, was a - a separate section, it came all together, it
 was all done in conjunction with it, but the drama department - was the one where - the policies were done, and the plays chosen, as I say, in these monthly meetings they had, and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 So you had a boss who was underneath Val?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Ye
s. No, Val wasn't really my boss. No. I had several bosses, we had what we called a drama booking manager. And he was head of all the contracts and the - and the money that they paid. But they all worked in conjunction with Val you see. And of course he w
as there a very long time. Because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did you see much of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Yes, quite a lot of him actually, yes. Because he was in Savoy Hill. And - we had - a lot of - lot to do with him then, and then he came straight on - to BH like that and really I thin
k I worked - indirectly with Val for many many years, practically all the years I was there. Because he retired - well he's a bit younger than I am. So he retired I supposed about - three or four years after I did. And - but I did come in contact with him
 a lot, because he was in charge of drama - department as such for many many years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 So in Drama bookings there were four girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Four girls and - and a man - who - who was the head, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 So were you all in the same office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Yes, we were 
all in the same office, and - or when I - no, I - I'm sorry, I - I made a mistake there. No, we were lucky. The four of us had different offices, we each had our - we had our own reception rooms and our own sec - secretaries which was very nice. Yes, no, 
I
'm sorry, that's wrong, it was - we did have separate rooms. And then all the queries that we had on money and that sort of thing - came to whoever happened to be the drama booking manager at - at the time. You see, because if any - any of the artists ask
s
 for money, to have their fees raised, well - I hadn't - I mean I was the senior one and when - the drama booking manager was ill or away on holiday I was in charge of it but - then I used to simply say to - we used to have discussions between the four of
 us -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Would you like to tell us a little about your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Yes - actually - my father was an architect, and - well I can't say much more than that about my mother because she - they were both - professionally my father was an architect, and he 
did a lot of private work in Wimbledon, you must tell me if it isn't right won't you, because - and we lived there, oh until my father died, and I think I - it was - 19 - he died in 1916 and I suppose I was about twenty - nine, no, not as much as that pro
b
ably, anyway, we moved then and we all scattered about and I've got - three sisters and - a brother, but both my parents are dead now of course, and we had a very happy childhood. Yes, very happy childhood, and I can remember - these are just a few little
 
- job things down - I can remember - a - a very old great aunt of mine who lived in Clapham. And this is what I'm really telling you, that I went to see her in a horse tram, if you can believe it, a horse tram which went up Clahpham Hill. I thought that m
i
ght give you an idea of the - of the past. And then of course we had - servants in plenty, as you can imagine, so that we didn't have - and I can always remember - them doing - scrubbing the - the - the steps you know with their real char - char's hat on 
and that sort of thing, and - oh yes, we didn't have really to do anything in the way of domestic work at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Tell me a bit about the servants, how many were there in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Well - in - in - in our family we had the cook, and we had a parl
ourmaid and we had a nurse. Because as I say we were a big family then, we were six, I had a brother who died some years ago, so there were six, because six is quite a lot to be done as you can imagine to keep a house going for six people. And I can remem
ber the days when - we had - if you wanted to go for drives when there weren't cars we had four wheelers to the station and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 handsome}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311  cabs instead of taxis which of course - was really rather fun then. And I can remember - when I was quite a child we had - s
ome big friends who lived on Wimbledon Common and had the most marvellous house, but - there was no transport in those days, public transport, so when I went to tea with her we used to go in the donkey chaise, the donkeys took us with a - a chaise over - 
over the - that sort of thing, and - we were a very happy family and we had lots and lots of friends and as I say, we lived there, my parents, we were all born in this one house and - it's where my parents went after they were married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did you see very much of the servants as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Oh yes, quite a lot. Oh yes, they weren't sort of - I mean the house wasn't big enough to have - divided it into staff - you know - premises like so many of them now. No, indeed, and we had very nice nurses and peopl
e like that, and my father did a lot of - he was - what is the - now I should know this - the - the - the science of works, is it entomology, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 etymology}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 ? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 Etymology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 . Well he was very interested in that and he used to give lectures - to one of the Wimbledon s
ocieties, I've forgotten now exactly what the name is, it's - you know, it's too long ago for me to remember that, but he used to do a lot of that, he was very very interested in it, and another thing he - he had also which was a great hobby of his, he - 
h
alf our back garden was - made into - a - pens for pigeons and he had really prize pigeons, and he used to send them to the Dairy Show and he - you know, used to - to - win all sorts of prizes, and - and that sort of thing - and we had a swing in a small 
w
hich I say was partly taken away. And then of course we had the Common which was very lovely, and we had the - the - pond and that sort of thing and when - when there was any ice we used to have skating on the pond and all that sort of thing, and - it rea
lly was a love - it was a lovely childhood I must say, I look back with it and used to have wonderful Christmases, you know, there was plenty of people to help us and all that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did you play mostly with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Ye
s. Yes, mostly, but we did have a - we used to go to - we had a lot of people who had young children, a lot of families who had young children as well as us, you know, and they - we went to - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13897837\charrsid9008311 parties}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311  galore at Christmastime particularly, and I was trying t
o think if there was anybody - oh I tell you - well you'll have heard of him anyway, he died a little while ago - for instance, just to - give you an idea how - nice people we had - you - remember the Graves's, you know, Rob - well Rob - Robert Graves the
 
poet, well his younger brother Charles - who was perhaps more our contemporary as children - he was a writer as you know too and he died a little while ago, well they lived in a house - a little farther up the road, and we used to go with them - an awful 
-
 an awful lot, and - I was trying to think who the other people - oh yes, and my father, that's right, my father built - or designed the really most beautiful house - later on, up on the top of the hill, and - we still - you know, used to have lots of - a
n
d I don't know whether you would know the name, probably not I don't think, the name of Adrian Daintry. No, well probably not, he wasn't in quite - he wasn't in the same category of being known as Robert and - and Charles were. But we did have some very i
nteresting friends, no doubt about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did you see very much of your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Yes, a lot about them, yes, a lot. Because - they were very - they were very devoted parents and - fortunately my father didn't have to - he was - his was domestic ar
chitecture, so he didn't have to go away and leave us, you know, like some people might have a profession, you know, that would mean they'd have to go away. No, and we had very delightful grandparents who lived in - well, my mother's parents - parents, I 
never knew my father's, they died before we - he was even married I think, but they were very delightful people and they lived at Surbiton. So we spent a lot of our childhood with them you know, at different times and - had great fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Supposing it was 
raining and you had to spend your time indoors what sort of things did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Oh what would I do? Ah, well now, wait a minute, at that age I have to - really have to think. Now it's a different things, I mean Radore reading, I could read all day lon
g, you know. I don't think I had - an awful lot of hobbies actually, I suppose I must have read a lot - in those days, but I've always loved reading. And of course when I was - older and at school - there again I don't quite know what I did when it was ra
ining, quite honestly I can't answer that one, I don't know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did you have sort of card games or family games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
We - oh we had a lot of card games, yes, I see, yes, we had a lot of card games we played, and - all sorts of games that were - charade
s and all that sort of thing you know and - musical chairs and all that sort of thing. And - then of course when I got older I was very very keen on sport, tennis particularly. Tennis and netball and hockey. They were the three that I - played at school.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Tell me about school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Well I was at a high school, the Wimbledon High school, and I was there - oh I suppose - oh I was there the whole time 'til the time I went to school, I was in the kindergarten there and then I went up into the bigger school
 and I stayed there - until just before 1914/18 war broke out, I had the - I finished on the - in the July, I suppose about three or four days before war - the first world war broke out. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 How did you get on at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Well - I am afraid aca
demically I was a very hard worker but I can't say I was academically good because I wasn't, I didn't profess to be but I was very hard working, I loved geography, I loved history and I loved English. And I've always loved - geography ever since, because 
-
 my great joy in life is travel. And - I think - I was much keener really, and I'll be perfectly honest, I was much keener on games and I was much better at games, but that doesn't say that I wasn't interested in work up to a point, I was. But I was - I h
ad - I had not got an academic brain, I mean I can't honestly say that with any truth, I haven't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 But you say you like reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Reading, I love reading, I love reading of all sorts. Very fond of biography, of - autobiography - travel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4021532 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 Did you learn to like reading at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10557675 HS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11872452\charrsid9008311 
Yes I did actually, I did, and of course another thing we - we - why we all - nearly all of us love the theatre because - these grandparents of ours - they took us to the theatre oh I can remember the first time I e
ver went when I was aged twelve, the first time I ever went at night. And I was so thrilled with it because - we had - we had a lovely - and that's really I think where we started and also where I started to get my love of travel because my - grandparents
 
were frightfully fond of travel. And - so I really think my - my main joys are reading - travel - and - you know - watching tennis and - oh show jumping I love watching, love watching ice skating, though of course I can't take part in those any more natur
ally because I'm - much too old, but - they are my great joy on the - on the box, I love watching it.
